<h2><a name="atan2" id="atan2">atan2</a></h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
Syntax:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="co2">#include &lt;cmath&gt;</span>
    <span class="kw4">double</span> atan2<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">double</span> y<span class="sy0">,</span> <span class="kw4">double</span> x <span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy0">;</span></pre>
<p>

The atan2() function computes the arc tangent of y/x, using the signs of the
arguments to compute the quadrant of the return value. The returned values are in the range [-pi, pi]. 
Note the order of the arguments passed to this function.
</p>

<p>
C++ also provides the following overloaded forms:

</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="co2">#include &lt;cmath&gt;</span>
    <span class="kw4">float</span> atan2<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">float</span> y<span class="sy0">,</span> <span class="kw4">float</span> x <span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy0">;</span> <span class="co1">// same as atan2f() in C99</span>
    <span class="kw4">long</span> <span class="kw4">double</span> atan2<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">long</span> <span class="kw4">double</span> y<span class="sy0">,</span> <span class="kw4">long</span> <span class="kw4">double</span> x <span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy0">;</span> <span class="co1">// same as atan2l() in C99</span></pre>
